# LeakSanitizer suppressions (Phase 5 T6 sanitizer sweep).
#
# Usage: LSAN_OPTIONS=suppressions=src/tests/sanitize.supp (Linux/ASan only;
# LeakSanitizer is not supported on macOS/AppleClang, see docs/BUILD.md and
# the sanitize-linux/sanitize-macos CI jobs).
#
# Suppression discipline (phase5-global-constraints.md): every entry below is
# a REAL leak, not a false positive -- each is disclosed here (and in the
# Phase 5 T6 task report) rather than fixed in place because a correct fix
# would need to touch fragile, narrowly-scoped production code this task did
# not have the coverage to safely verify. Each entry names the exact
# functions and explains why.

# shapemob.cpp's new_mob()/implement_proto() ("shape mobile" -> "implement",
# an admin-only mob-prototype editor command): implement_proto() does a
# wholesale copy-assignment `*proto = *SHAPE_PROTO(ch)->proto;` (mob_proto
# slot <- scratch proto) that overwrites the destination's existing profs/
# name/short_descr/long_descr/description pointers with the scratch proto's
# (usually null-or-different) ones, orphaning whatever the destination
# previously owned -- and the scratch proto object itself (new_mob()'s
# CREATE1(SHAPE_PROTO(ch)->proto, char_data) plus its four CREATE()'d name/
# short_descr/long_descr/description strings) is never freed after
# implement_proto() finishes copying out of it. implement_proto()'s own
# comment block (shapemob.cpp:1788-1799, including an already-commented-out
# partial RELEASE() attempt) documents that this function was previously hand-
# tuned around a real std::map-corruption bug (a raw memcpy corrupting
# player_damage_details::damage_map) -- ShapeMob.
# ImplementProtoCopiesMobProtoWithoutCorruptingItsDamageMap
# (shapemob_tests.cpp) is the RED/GREEN regression test guarding that exact
# fix. Correctly closing the leak requires auditing every mob_proto/scratch-
# proto ownership transfer in this function without disturbing that
# copy-assignment's carefully-chosen semantics -- out of scope for this
# task's sweep; tracked as follow-up work, not silently dropped. Only exercised
# by this one admin-only "shape mobile" editor command (no other caller in the
# tree).
#
# Suppressed by the TEST's own TestBody frame, not by new_mob/implement_proto/
# clear_char symbol names: the orphaned fake_mob_proto[0].profs allocation's
# own stack trace bottoms out in clear_char() (called directly by the test,
# not by implement_proto()) -- clear_char() is far too common a symbol to
# suppress globally, but every one of this test's four leak stacks (new_mob's
# proto+strings, implement_proto's replacement strings, and this
# clear_char()-allocated profs block) shares this exact TestBody frame, so
# suppressing by it is both complete and precisely scoped to this one test.
leak:ShapeMob_ImplementProtoCopiesMobProtoWithoutCorruptingItsDamageMap_Test::TestBody

# db.cpp's build_player_index(): resets top_of_p_table to -1 and rebuilds
# player_table from scratch by rescanning the players/ directories, without
# ever freeing whatever player_table already held (each entry's
# create_entry()-strdup'd .name, plus the table array itself). Confirmed via
# the single production call site (db.cpp boot_db(), called exactly once at
# boot with player_table still empty) that this is NOT reachable in the real
# game -- it is exercised here only because DbLoader.
# BuildPlayerIndexRemainsConsistentAfterVersionedMigrationRetiresStaleFlatFile
# calls account::migrate_legacy_character_by_name() (which populates one
# player_table entry via ensure_player_index_entry()/create_entry()) BEFORE
# calling build_player_index(), an ordering boot_db() itself never produces.
# A correct fix (freeing the previous table if build_player_index() is ever
# called non-fresh) is still worth doing defensively, but is a production
# function change outside this task's leak-sweep scope; tracked as follow-up,
# not silently dropped.
leak:DbLoader_BuildPlayerIndexRemainsConsistentAfterVersionedMigrationRetiresStaleFlatFile_Test::TestBody

